Dr. Ray Peat talked about how nutritionists hyperfocused on substances related to growth like methionine as essential due to the livestock industry but I think a lot of it comes from WW1 German famines when they had a highly advanced scientific culture together with lack of food.

During WW1 German professors did a bunch of studies of the nature of adding urea or sawdust to sheep's diets and seeing if they could gain more weight on it on limited calories, also where a lot of the obsession on dietary fats, how long you could live on zero fat, etc., started.

In conditions of famine it's normal to focus on substances that can increase growth or slow starvation down, also macronutrient essentiality is a life or death issue when the state runs out of butter and other fats and has to do paraffin chemistry on coal, a lot of this remained.
